### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

The async pipe provides a clean way to write reactive applications, until it comes to error handling with them. Although this can be handled by creating a separate stream it isn't necessarily very intuitive.

The new control flow has been excellent for creating more ergonomic templates with things like `@empty` for ng-for and `@else` for ng-if, and `@error` (or something similarly named such as `@catch`) could be a useful tool. 

### Proposed solution

Introducing `@error` as part of the normal control flow could be a useful tool for creating reactive applications. The full syntax might be something like:
```
@if ( user$ | async; as user ) {
    <app-user-component [user]="user"><app-user-component>
} @else {
    <app-loading-component></app-loading-component>
} @error {
    <app-error-component></app-error-component>
}
```

### Alternatives considered

Guidelines on async pipe error handling, although this could be end up being far too opinionated.

### Command

build

### Is this a regression?

- [X] Yes, this behavior used to work in the previous version

### The previous version in which this bug was not present was

v17

### Description

Background: Mostly vanilla angular application using PWA since Angular ~5 doing normal `ng update`s.

Service worker only being used for caching static assets and serving them offline

---

When upgrading to v18 I accepted the migration to `:application` - the schematic did not migrate the `build.configurations.production.serviceWorker` from a boolean (`true`)

```
ng serve --proxy-config proxy-dev.conf.json  --configuration production
Error: Schema validation failed with the following errors:
  Data path "/serviceWorker" must be string.
  Data path "/serviceWorker" must be equal to constant.
  Data path "/serviceWorker" must match exactly one schema in oneOf.
```

Through trial and error I discovered the "correct"  new value for the `build.configurations.production.serviceWorker` field: `ngsw-config.json` (aside -- FR: link the schema from [the migration docs](https://angular.dev/tools/cli/build-system-migration)? ðŸ™)

The service worker appeared to fetch and serve assets as expected **but** just before promoting from canary to prod I did an extra QA pass (it was sus that my `angular.json` wasn't properly migrated) and discovered that refreshing while offline now reported a 504

![Screenshot_20240818_113433](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/34ba9b97-6140-49e7-a469-215318d4aa48)

The above 504 is being served from the Service Worker and it appears the handling logic isn't serving the cached copy on network error anymore.

* â›” Running my v18 build locally with `ng serve --configuration production` shared the same issue
* âœ… Reverting to v17 and it again worked as expected.
* âœ… Making a new v18 build with `angular.json` reverted to the v17 version (using `:build` rather than `:application`) works as expected when using `ng serve --configuration production`
* â›” Making a new v18 build with the reverted `angular.json` and substituting `:build` for `:build-esbuild` failed to register any service worker 
  * This seems like a separate issue, the `:application` build does still register the SW and serve assets

### Minimal Reproduction

I assume (but have not tested) this would affect any PWA-enabled repo upgraded from v17 to v18 which performs the migration.

I have a workaround that allows me to upgrade to v18 (using the old & busted webpack builder)

